default10. What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the defaultUK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?default&#xa0;
defaultA large part of the UK domestic mining and quarrying industry is owned and operated by relatively few large multinational companies, the majority of which are foreign-owned. A high percentage of total outp
defaultut of construction aggregates in the UK 
defaultis
default from quarries operated by 
defaultfour companies
default. These companies are all vertically integrated and include 
defaultcement manufacturing 
defaultin the UK or Europe. The indigenous silica sand and ball clay/ kaolin industries are also do
defaultminated by just two large, foreign owned companies. Ownership of the coal industry across the UK is more diverse. 
defaultThe
default consolidation of mining and quarrying companies
default is partly
default 
defaultin
default response to competition for land use. The commercial risk involved in 
defaultsetting
default aside time and financial resources 
defaultneeded to obtain a licence to operate 
default(planning permission and environmental permits) 
defaultin the UK is relatively high by both world and European standards. The response of the market to this risk has been for companies to r
defaulteplenish reserves by acquisition (in order to access additional permitted sites or to deny them to rivals) and by vertical integration (for cement companies to secure supplies of vital aggregate raw materials). The result is a relatively small group of lar
defaultge companies who have sufficient investment capability to meet permitting costs and maintain a portfolio of different supply options. 
defaultThis situation may present
default 
defaulta barrier
default to entry for smaller local operators
default. It may also encourage 
defaultconsolidation of producti
defaulton at fewer, larger quarries where 
defaultlarger
default companies can take advantage of economies of scale
default, as well as
default the ‘trading’ of sites with permitted reserves between companies
default and the
default giving up of dormant sites in scenic areas such as National Parks in exchange 
defaultfor a licence to operate elsewhere.
